{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17747"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17747"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0,0.86,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75862"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61375"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"3234"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"6612"},{"type":"tags","id":"9014"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75862"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of tremor, slowness of movement, and stiffness. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals a resting tremor in his right hand, bradykinesia, and increased muscle tone in his limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Essential tremor","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis","Huntington\u0027s disease","Parkinson\u0027s disease","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and examination findings consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which is caused by the degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra pars compacta. This leads to reduced dopamine input into the dorsal striatum, resulting in the classic motor symptoms of tremor, bradykinesia, and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEssential tremor\u003C/strong\u003E presents with an action tremor rather than a resting tremor and lacks the bradykinesia and rigidity seen in Parkinson\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a variety of neurological symptoms in a \u0027waxing and waning\u0027 course. It is due to demyelination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder that presents with chorea, psychiatric symptoms, and cognitive decline, rather than the resting tremor and bradykinesia seen in Parkinson\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyotrophic lateral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects motor neurons, leading to muscle weakness and atrophy, rather than the tremor and rigidity seen in Parkinson\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra pars compacta is the aetiology of Parkinson\u0027s disease.","Parkinson\u0027s disease leads to reduced dopamine input into the dorsal striatum, affecting motor control.","Symptoms of Parkinson\u0027s disease include tremor, bradykinesia, rigidity, and postural instability."],"references":["DeMaagd G, Philip A. Parkinson\u0027s Disease and Its Management: Part 1: Disease Entity, Risk Factors, Pathophysiology, Clinical Presentation, and Diagnosis. P T. 2015 Aug;40(8):504-32. PMID: 26236139; PMCID: PMC4517533.","Clarke CE. Parkinson\u0027s disease. BMJ. 2007 Sep 1;335(7617):441-5. doi: 10.1136/bmj.39289.437454.AD. PMID: 17762036; PMCID: PMC1962892.","Balestrino R, Schapira AHV. Parkinson disease. Eur J Neurol. 2020 Jan;27(1):27-42. doi: 10.1111/ene.14108. Epub 2019 Nov 27. PMID: 31631455.","Zafar S, Yaddanapudi SS. Parkinson Disease. 2023 Aug 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29261972."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61375"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61375"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T05:03:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T05:03:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10461"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75862"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synony